#X text 418 311 no loadbang;
#X text 42 125 The default range is from 0 to 127 \, but you can change it with the range message/flag. A float sets and outputs values \, which get clipped to the [knob]'s range. A 'set' message only sets the value (no output)., f 71;
#X text 42 7 Click and drag or click and use mouse wheel/touchpad scrolling for chaning the knob's value. By default \, the angular range is 320 degrees. The object also draws an 'arc' by default with its own color (besides background and foreground color). The arc is useful to display the initial and final range position. You can change this with the 'arc' or 'angle' messages \, properties or flags. A full 360 degree is possible and the arc color is then useful to differentiate from fully turned down (showing the arc color) to fully turned up (showing foreground color). Without an arc \, you have a full circle at the center instead \, and the arc color also sets its color., f 71;
#X msg 322 288 reload;
#X msg 297 221 load 25;
#X text 348 382 alt/option+click reloads;
#X text 26 550 The 'load' message sets the initial value for when the object is loaded. A 'load' message without float saves the current value as the load value. The 'reload' message sets to the load value again and it is the same as alt/option+click. In 'savestate' mode \, when you save the patch \, the current knob's value becomes the 'load' value. Note that the [savestate] object is needed if you use [knob] in an abstraction. In 'loadbang' mode (default) \, the load value is output at load time., f 78;
#X msg 285 199 range -10 10 \, dirty;
#X text 26 436 Unlike setting things via the properties window \, when changing parameters via messages doesn't dirty the patch. This means that if you close the patch it won't ask you to save changes. In order to force asking to save you can use the 'dirty' message after changing something (like it's done above after changing the range to from -10 to 10)., f 78;
#X msg 174 314 default 50;
#X text 26 499 The 'arcstart' value is where the arc starts \, just 'arcstart' sets the current value as the start value. Same goes for default \, where just 'default' sets the current value to the default value is where you reset to when double clicking on the object \, so does the 'reset' message., f 78;
#X text 345 342 double click restores to the default state (same as 'reset'), f 21;
