#X text 378 11 Use the "learn" message or "Ctrl+Click" ("command+click" on mac) for "MIDI learn". This mechanism sends a bang to a given send name or var name followed by "-learn". Below \, the object has a "\$0-knob2" send name \, so it goes to "\$0-knob2-learn". You can use this to connect to a [midi.learn] object that actually offers a "MIDI Learn" mechanism. Try it below. Anyway \, even if you're not sending values anywhere \, the send name is needed for this. The MIDI forget follows the same mechanism and is triggered by the 'forget' message or "Shift+Ctrl+Click". Note that the shortcuts don't work in 'read only' mode., f 70;
#X text 406 584 IMPORTANT: In this case \, you may want the same send symbol for different knobs that control different parameters. This is why the "var" symbol is also used for other send symbols like learn and forget., f 64;
#X msg 462 437 learn;
#X obj 419 530 bng 21 250 50 0 empty empty empty 0 -12 0 16 #dfdfdf #000000 #000000;
#X obj 419 501 r \$0-x-learn;
#X text 390 289 Use "var' to set a variable and send values to variables in [value] or [var] objects. Note that you also can do that if you have a send name that matches a variable name \, but with the 'var' symbol you bypass sending to a [receive] object and just set the variable directly. Like send/receive \, you need to escape dollar signs in messages. This is particularly useful if you have a 'param' name \, in which case you cannot send values to a [value] object with the same 'send' name \, for instance. HINT: use [var] with [savestate] objects to save the current state of GUIs., f 67;
